            "creation_date": 1439474713,
            "body": "<p>This concrete example Juliano is referring to is from the hybris commerce suite.\nHybris has the concept of extensions that have dependencies on each other. Each extension defines their own application context which has access to its inherited application contexts (from those extensions that are declared as dependencies).<\/p>\n\n<p>In this example there is an abstractPopulatingConverter bean declaration declared at the root application context where its declared java class is abstract.\nHowever, in other application context further down the dependency tree there is an alias definition for this \"abstractPopulatingConverter\" that points to a bean definitions with a concrete class.\nThat's why in a lot of cases (namely the ones that are even further down the dependency tree) using the parent=\"abstractPopulatingConverter\" works as it points to the new bean defined by the alias.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 31990493,
            "question_id": 30625320
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/86c698bde49330b20065bba29f9f0c5d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 3837441,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3181444,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3181444/dmitry-nikiforov",
                "reputation": 3068,
                "display_name": "Dmitry Nikiforov"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1433348446,
            "creation_date": 1433348446,
            "body": "<p>This is the very common message when Spring container faces with absatract Java class (not abstract bean). Check your com.java.bean.AbstractBeanClass code and probably you can find \"public abstract class\". <\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 30625582,
            "question_id": 30625320
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4ec21df1e55febf8deb2e3b24b9cb39b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 195331,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 438154,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/438154/sotirios-delimanolis",
                "reputation": 281049,
                "display_name": "Sotirios Delimanolis",
                "accept_rate": 98
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1433349979,
            "creation_date": 1433349979,
            "body": "<blockquote>\n  <p>What am I missing here?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>I don't know what's going on in your other project, but Spring cannot instantiate beans for classes that are <code>abstract<\/code>. <\/p>\n\n<p>Concerning <code>abstract<\/code> beans, the <a href=\"http://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/spring-framework-reference/html/beans.html#beans-child-bean-definitions\" rel=\"nofollow\">Spring documentation<\/a> states<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>A child bean definition inherits configuration data from a parent definition. <\/p>\n  \n  <p>[...]<\/p>\n  \n  <p>A child bean definition uses the bean class from the parent definition\n  if none is specified, but can also override it. In the latter case,\n  the child bean class must be compatible with the parent, that is, it\n  must accept the parent\u2019s property values.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>In other words, an bean definition declared with <code>abstract=\"true\"<\/code> is simply used as a template for other beans.<\/p>\n\n<p>Java does not allow instantiation of <code>abstract<\/code> classes. Spring cannot overrule this language feature. Spring cannot instantiate beans of <code>abstract<\/code> class types.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 30626051,
            "question_id": 30625320
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/sHNM6.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 3059647,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2592600,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2592600/juliano-a-felipe",
                "reputation": 584,
                "display_name": "Juliano A. Felipe",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": -1,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1433957338,
            "creation_date": 1433957338,
            "body": "<p>Found the answer:<\/p>\n\n<p>Indeed, like <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/users/438154/sotirios-delimanolis\">Sotirios Delimanolis<\/a> commented, <em>\"You must have something else going on, proxying of some kind maybe\"<\/em>, Spring has a proxy that instantiate this type of bean declaration, but it can't instantiate the bean without its methods (which are just declared in the abstract class, not implemented).<br>\nSo you must \"implement\" these methods, like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;bean id=\"childBean\" parent=\"abstractBean\"&gt;\n   &lt;lookup-method name=\"notImplementedMethod\" bean=\"anotherBean\"/&gt;\n&lt;/bean&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The <em>anotherBean<\/em> must be the same type as <em>notImplementedMethod<\/em>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 30763313,
            "question_id": 30625320,
            "last_edit_date": 1495542757
        }
